    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Debates Are Over. Now It's the Voters' Turn.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Del Janik letter comments on October 18 article on final presidential debate between Vice Pres Al Gore and Gov George W Bush</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush and Gore, in Last Debate, Stage Vigorous Give-and-Take'' (front page, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush and Gore, in Last Debate, Stage Vigorous Give-and-Take'' (front page, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>Having sat through all three presidential debates, which despite the different formats consisted largely of set pieces and stump-speech excerpts repeated each week nearly without variation, I have a suggestion for the Commission on Presidential Debates for 2004.</p>
        <p>Topics should be limited on a given evening to domestic policy, economics or foreign affairs. Such restrictions might encourage the candidates to rise above the sound-bite level and offer them a clearer opportunity to give genuine and detailed expression to their ideals and proposals.</p>
        <p>DEL JANIK  Cortland, N.Y., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
